00:00:21.240 --> 00:00:24.520
ANDREW LO: Well, if you remember
last time where we left off,

00:00:24.520 --> 00:00:27.270
we were talking about
risk and return.

00:00:27.270 --> 00:00:29.340
And we said that we
were going to make

00:00:29.340 --> 00:00:32.759
the following simplifying
assumption, which

00:00:32.759 --> 00:00:37.230
is that we're going to
assume that investors

00:00:37.230 --> 00:00:42.630
like expected return,
and they do not like risk

00:00:42.630 --> 00:00:44.970
as measured by volatility.

00:00:44.970 --> 00:00:46.020
All right?

00:00:46.020 --> 00:00:49.920
And so the way that we
depict it graphically

00:00:49.920 --> 00:00:54.150
is to use a graph
where the x-axis is

00:00:54.150 --> 00:00:58.770
standard deviation of
your entire portfolio,

00:00:58.770 --> 00:01:03.600
and the y-axis is the expected
return of that portfolio.

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:09.030
And the question is,
where on this graph

00:01:09.030 --> 00:01:12.720
can we get to, given the
securities that we have access

00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:16.790
to, that will maximize
our level of happiness.

00:01:16.790 --> 00:01:18.960
Where happiness,
again, is assumed

00:01:18.960 --> 00:01:23.550
to mean higher expected rate
of return and lower risk,

00:01:23.550 --> 00:01:26.860
as measured by variance
or standard deviation.

00:01:26.860 --> 00:01:29.940
So for example, if you take
a look at this simple graph

00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:33.400
and you ask the question, where
on the graph do you want to be,

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:35.940
you would like to
be always going

00:01:35.940 --> 00:01:38.050
in the northwest direction.

00:01:38.050 --> 00:01:38.550
Right?

00:01:38.550 --> 00:01:42.210
Because north means higher
expected return and west

00:01:42.210 --> 00:01:45.120
means lower risk.

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:52.040
So obviously, if we could,
we'd love to be on this axis

00:01:52.040 --> 00:01:54.420
all the way, way up.

00:01:54.420 --> 00:01:56.130
Right?

00:01:56.130 --> 00:01:58.970
No risk, lots of return.

00:01:58.970 --> 00:02:01.040
That's an example
of an arbitrage.

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:03.050
And we know that
that can't happen

00:02:03.050 --> 00:02:06.300
very easily because otherwise
everybody would be there.

00:02:06.300 --> 00:02:09.740
And pretty soon it would
wipe out that opportunity.

00:02:09.740 --> 00:02:13.370
So the question from the
portfolio construction

00:02:13.370 --> 00:02:17.300
perspective is now a little bit
sharper than it was last week

00:02:17.300 --> 00:02:19.200
when we started down this path.

00:02:19.200 --> 00:02:23.250
Now we want to
construct a portfolio,

00:02:23.250 --> 00:02:26.090
we want to take a
collection of securities

00:02:26.090 --> 00:02:31.550
and weight them in order
to be as happy as possible.

00:02:31.550 --> 00:02:36.840
Meaning, we want to be
as northwest as possible.

00:02:36.840 --> 00:02:39.050
So let's see how we
go about doing that.

00:02:39.050 --> 00:02:42.570
One thing we could do is just
pick an individual stock.

00:02:42.570 --> 00:02:46.160
So if you have these four
stocks to pick from, then

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:48.950
to go as northwest
as possible, you're

00:02:48.950 --> 00:02:55.760
sort of looking at Merck
as, you know, the extreme.

00:02:55.760 --> 00:02:58.400
But it's not at all clear
whether or not that's something

00:02:58.400 --> 00:02:59.360
that you really want.

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:02.840
Because, for example,
General Motors,

00:03:02.840 --> 00:03:07.400
while it has a lower expected
return than Merck, it does

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:09.200
have a bit of a lower risk.

00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:14.310
And for some people, that
might actually be preferred.

00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:19.550
So at this point, we don't have
a lot of hard recommendations

00:03:19.550 --> 00:03:22.780
to provide you with, without
any further analysis.

00:03:22.780 --> 00:03:25.120
So we're going to do some
further analysis today.

00:03:25.120 --> 00:03:29.900
And the analysis is to ask
the question, all right, what

00:03:29.900 --> 00:03:36.330
are the properties of mean and
variance for a given portfolio,

00:03:36.330 --> 00:03:39.620
not just for an
individual security.

00:03:39.620 --> 00:03:42.440
So it turns out that there's a
relatively straightforward way

00:03:42.440 --> 00:03:43.410
of answering this.

00:03:43.410 --> 00:03:45.260
And let me just go
through the calculations

00:03:45.260 --> 00:03:47.090
and then we can see
what that implies

00:03:47.090 --> 00:03:51.770
for where we want to be in that
mean-standard deviation graph.

00:03:51.770 --> 00:03:54.680
So the mean of a
particular stock I'm

00:03:54.680 --> 00:03:59.910
going to write as expectation
of Ri, or mu i, for short.

00:03:59.910 --> 00:04:01.760
The variance of a
particular stock

00:04:01.760 --> 00:04:04.550
I'm going to write
as sigma squared i,

00:04:04.550 --> 00:04:07.970
or the standard deviation
is then just sigma i.

00:04:07.970 --> 00:04:09.320
OK?

00:04:09.320 --> 00:04:13.430
And it turns out, you
can show this rigorously.

00:04:13.430 --> 00:04:15.860
I won't do that, but you
can take a look at that

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:17.750
if you are unconvinced.

00:04:17.750 --> 00:04:21.260
It turns out that if you
construct a weighted average

00:04:21.260 --> 00:04:25.310
of stocks so that the
return of the portfolio

00:04:25.310 --> 00:04:28.940
is given by that
top line, R sub p,

00:04:28.940 --> 00:04:33.170
then when you take the expected
value of that top line, what

00:04:33.170 --> 00:04:36.390
you get is the middle line.

00:04:36.390 --> 00:04:41.360
In other words, the expected
return of a portfolio

00:04:41.360 --> 00:04:44.450
is just equal to the exact
same weighted averages

00:04:44.450 --> 00:04:48.600
of the expected rates of return
of the individual components.

00:04:48.600 --> 00:04:51.140
So you understand the
difference between the second

00:04:51.140 --> 00:04:53.180
and the first line
in that red box?

00:04:53.180 --> 00:04:55.230
That's a very
important distinction.

00:04:55.230 --> 00:04:59.360
The top line is basically
an accounting identity.

00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:02.540
It says that when you want to
compute the actual realized

00:05:02.540 --> 00:05:04.640
return in your
portfolio, you just

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:07.460
take a weighted average of what
you did on each stock, what

00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:08.920
your return is on each stock.

00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:11.210
That's an accounting identity.

00:05:11.210 --> 00:05:14.480
The second line is not
an accounting identity.

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:16.070
It comes from an
accounting identity.

00:05:16.070 --> 00:05:20.050
But what it says
is that on average,

00:05:20.050 --> 00:05:22.780
the rate of return
of your portfolio

00:05:22.780 --> 00:05:28.060
is equal to a weighted average
of the average rates of return

00:05:28.060 --> 00:05:30.890
on each of the components
of your portfolio.

00:05:30.890 --> 00:05:31.390
OK?

00:05:31.390 --> 00:05:34.580
That's a very
important principle.

00:05:34.580 --> 00:05:38.100
Any questions about
that before we move on?

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:38.600
OK.

00:05:38.600 --> 00:05:42.250
So I'm going to write that as a
shorthand for the portfolio, mu

00:05:42.250 --> 00:05:43.270
sub p.

00:05:43.270 --> 00:05:45.560
So mu sub p is just equal
to this whole expression

00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:47.180
right here.

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:47.720
All right.

00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:53.210
So what we've now deduced is
that the mean of my portfolio

00:05:53.210 --> 00:05:56.150
is simply the weighted
average of the means of each

00:05:56.150 --> 00:05:59.660
of the securities
in the portfolio.

00:05:59.660 --> 00:06:02.060
What I'm going to turn to next
is a much more complicated

00:06:02.060 --> 00:06:08.060
calculation, which is, what is
the variance of my portfolio.

00:06:08.060 --> 00:06:11.040
It turns out that the
variance of the portfolio

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:15.060
is not a simple weighted
average of the variances

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:16.510
of my individual securities.

00:06:16.510 --> 00:06:17.940
This is where it
gets complicated,

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:20.460
and also where it gets really
interesting and valuable

00:06:20.460 --> 00:06:22.391
from the investor's perspective.

00:06:22.391 --> 00:06:22.890
OK.

00:06:22.890 --> 00:06:24.220
Let's do the calculation.

00:06:24.220 --> 00:06:29.220
You're going to have to dredge
up your old DMD knowledge here

00:06:29.220 --> 00:06:33.560
of how to compute variances
of sums of random variables.

00:06:33.560 --> 00:06:37.230
The variance of my
portfolio return, R sub p,

00:06:37.230 --> 00:06:41.430
is simply equal to the expected
value of the excess return

00:06:41.430 --> 00:06:44.450
of that portfolio, in
excess of its mean,

00:06:44.450 --> 00:06:47.760
right, squared, and then
take the expectation of that.

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:51.660
And remember that the
return of the portfolio

00:06:51.660 --> 00:06:53.520
is just a weighted
average of the returns

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:55.050
of the individual securities.

00:06:55.050 --> 00:06:58.470
And the mean of the portfolio is
just the same weighted average

00:06:58.470 --> 00:07:00.510
of the means of the securities.

00:07:00.510 --> 00:07:03.690
So when you plug those
relationships in, what you get

00:07:03.690 --> 00:07:06.060
is that the variance is
simply equal to the expected

00:07:06.060 --> 00:07:12.781
value of the square of
this long weighted average.

00:07:12.781 --> 00:07:14.905
So you've got a weighted
average, a bunch of terms,

00:07:14.905 --> 00:07:15.840
right?

00:07:15.840 --> 00:07:18.340
And then you square
that and then

00:07:18.340 --> 00:07:20.540
you take the expected value.

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:26.680
Well, if you've got n terms
in that weighted average,

00:07:26.680 --> 00:07:30.379
and you square that n
terms, how many terms

00:07:30.379 --> 00:07:31.420
comes out of that square?

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:37.490
Anybody?

00:07:37.490 --> 00:07:40.910
n terms, and you
square those n terms,

00:07:40.910 --> 00:07:44.290
so those n terms
multiplied by itself,

00:07:44.290 --> 00:07:46.660
how many terms do you
get when you do that?

00:07:46.660 --> 00:07:47.160
Yeah?

00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:48.880
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:48.880 --> 00:07:52.740
ANDREW LO: Well, why
not just n squared?

00:07:52.740 --> 00:07:54.900
You're thinking about the
unique elements, maybe,

00:07:54.900 --> 00:07:55.830
the off diagonal.

00:07:55.830 --> 00:07:57.690
I'm talking about all of them.

00:07:57.690 --> 00:08:00.100
So with n terms,
when you square it,

00:08:00.100 --> 00:08:06.870
n terms multiplied by n terms,
you get n times n terms,

00:08:06.870 --> 00:08:09.710
n squared terms.

00:08:09.710 --> 00:08:15.130
And so these n squared
terms all look like this.

00:08:15.130 --> 00:08:18.290
They all look like
omega i times omega

00:08:18.290 --> 00:08:22.180
j multiplied by the
excess return of i

00:08:22.180 --> 00:08:23.920
times the excess return of j.

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:26.190
Sometimes i equals j.

00:08:26.190 --> 00:08:30.450
And when that happens,
you get omega i squared

00:08:30.450 --> 00:08:34.049
times the variance
of security i.

00:08:34.049 --> 00:08:37.169
But when i does not
equal to j, then you're

00:08:37.169 --> 00:08:42.059
going to get omega i times
omega j times the covariance

00:08:42.059 --> 00:08:43.960
between the return on i and j.

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:51.020
And another way of
writing that covariance

00:08:51.020 --> 00:08:53.840
is equal to the
correlation between i

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:56.940
and j multiplied by the
standard deviation of i

00:08:56.940 --> 00:09:00.410
and the standard deviation of j.

00:09:00.410 --> 00:09:04.762
The point is that when we look
at the variance of a portfolio,

00:09:04.762 --> 00:09:06.470
it's not just the
simple weighted average

00:09:06.470 --> 00:09:09.290
of the variances of
the component stocks.

00:09:09.290 --> 00:09:14.150
It's actually a weighted average
of all the cross products,

00:09:14.150 --> 00:09:20.140
where the weights are also the
cross products of the weights.

00:09:20.140 --> 00:09:21.380
So it's these.

00:09:21.380 --> 00:09:22.567
It's all of these.

00:09:22.567 --> 00:09:23.900
And how many of these are there?

00:09:23.900 --> 00:09:29.240
Well, i goes from 1 to n, j
goes from 1 to n, n times n,

00:09:29.240 --> 00:09:30.500
you get n squared of these.

00:09:30.500 --> 00:09:34.840
So this actually has
a nice representation.

00:09:34.840 --> 00:09:37.130
It actually comes
out of a table.

00:09:37.130 --> 00:09:37.880
Right?

00:09:37.880 --> 00:09:42.260
So you can think of all of the
portfolio weights multiplied

00:09:42.260 --> 00:09:44.990
by the excess returns
on one dimension

00:09:44.990 --> 00:09:49.340
of the table, the columns,
and the exact same entries

00:09:49.340 --> 00:09:50.480
in the rows.

00:09:50.480 --> 00:09:54.290
You've got n columns,
n rows, n times n,

00:09:54.290 --> 00:09:57.650
or n squared
elements that make up

00:09:57.650 --> 00:10:01.620
the variance of your portfolio.

00:10:01.620 --> 00:10:04.280
So this is where it
gets really complicated.

00:10:04.280 --> 00:10:06.530
But this is why we have
computers and spreadsheets

00:10:06.530 --> 00:10:08.550
and things like that.

00:10:08.550 --> 00:10:12.200
So in order to figure out the
variance of your portfolio,

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:15.200
you've got to basically add all
of the elements in this table.

00:10:15.200 --> 00:10:17.690
You've got n squared
things to add up

00:10:17.690 --> 00:10:21.740
to get the variance
of your portfolio.

00:10:21.740 --> 00:10:25.830
And the insight of
modern finance theory--

00:10:25.830 --> 00:10:28.310
the reason that Harry
Markowitz won the Nobel Prize

00:10:28.310 --> 00:10:30.890
in economics for this idea--

00:10:30.890 --> 00:10:35.810
is that when you add up all
of these different elements,

00:10:35.810 --> 00:10:39.110
you can get results that
are very different from just

00:10:39.110 --> 00:10:41.390
looking at one or two stocks.

00:10:41.390 --> 00:10:43.700
Because, in
particular, there are

00:10:43.700 --> 00:10:46.970
some cases where
these cross products

00:10:46.970 --> 00:10:51.190
are either small or
maybe even negative.

00:10:51.190 --> 00:10:52.890
And in that case,
it actually helps

00:10:52.890 --> 00:10:58.590
you to reduce the overall
riskiness of your portfolio.

00:10:58.590 --> 00:11:00.180
This is the intuition.

00:11:00.180 --> 00:11:02.700
This is the
mathematics underlying,

00:11:02.700 --> 00:11:04.890
don't put all your
eggs in one basket.

00:11:04.890 --> 00:11:08.040
When you don't put all your
eggs in one basket, what you're

00:11:08.040 --> 00:11:10.320
getting, what you're
benefiting from,

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:13.410
are these cross
products that can either

00:11:13.410 --> 00:11:18.110
be small or negative,
and will ultimately

00:11:18.110 --> 00:11:22.702
reduce the fluctuations
of your portfolio.

00:11:22.702 --> 00:11:25.160
Another way of thinking about
it is that some stocks go up,

00:11:25.160 --> 00:11:26.550
some stocks go down.

00:11:26.550 --> 00:11:30.380
And if they don't go up and
down in the exact same way,

00:11:30.380 --> 00:11:34.010
if they are unrelated
or less related,

00:11:34.010 --> 00:11:37.460
then when you put it all
together in a portfolio

00:11:37.460 --> 00:11:43.880
it dampens the riskiness
of your overall holdings.

00:11:43.880 --> 00:11:45.100
OK.

00:11:45.100 --> 00:11:48.520
So there are n squared
elements that you

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:52.360
have to add up in order to
get the portfolio variance.

00:11:52.360 --> 00:11:56.140
It's literally the sum of all
of the entries in this table.

00:11:56.140 --> 00:12:00.280
And the point of the
next few bullet points

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:03.430
is that there are a
lot more covariances

00:12:03.430 --> 00:12:05.920
than there are variances.

00:12:05.920 --> 00:12:08.680
The variances are along the
diagonal of that table, right?

00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:10.930
That's the variance
of the first stock,

00:12:10.930 --> 00:12:12.533
the variance of the
second stock, dot,

00:12:12.533 --> 00:12:15.530
dot, dot, the variance
of the n stock.

00:12:15.530 --> 00:12:18.210
Those are how volatile
the individual stocks are.

00:12:18.210 --> 00:12:20.640
But there are only n of those.

00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:24.690
There are n squared minus
n of the other stuff.

00:12:24.690 --> 00:12:26.955
That's where you were thinking
about n minus 1, right?

00:12:26.955 --> 00:12:32.520
It's n squared minus n,
or n times n minus 1.

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:35.100
Other non-diagonal entries.

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:38.940
So what this suggests is that
the covariances are a lot more

00:12:38.940 --> 00:12:43.470
important in determining the
riskiness of your portfolio

00:12:43.470 --> 00:12:46.180
than the riskiness of
the individual stocks.

00:12:46.180 --> 00:12:48.600
You know, Intel looks
like a scary stock

00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:50.280
because it's really volatile.

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:53.702
But when you've got n
Intels in your portfolio,

00:12:53.702 --> 00:12:55.410
even though each of
the individual stocks

00:12:55.410 --> 00:12:57.900
is scary, what you have
to keep your eye on

00:12:57.900 --> 00:13:00.180
is how they are correlated.

00:13:00.180 --> 00:13:03.840
Because the correlations
in a portfolio of n

00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:06.450
stocks is actually
more important

00:13:06.450 --> 00:13:08.010
than the individual variances.

00:13:08.010 --> 00:13:10.830
The individual variances
matter, but they

00:13:10.830 --> 00:13:13.860
don't matter nearly as
much as the covariances.

00:13:13.860 --> 00:13:15.000
OK?

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:16.950
So now I'm going
to do an example.

00:13:16.950 --> 00:13:21.150
It's hard to get intuition
for n by n matrices,

00:13:21.150 --> 00:13:25.110
unless you're Rain Man,
or some incredible genius.

00:13:25.110 --> 00:13:27.760
The way that I think about this
is, let's look at two assets.

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:28.260
OK?

00:13:28.260 --> 00:13:31.110
If I can understand two assets,
I can sort generalize and think

00:13:31.110 --> 00:13:32.460
about n assets.

00:13:32.460 --> 00:13:34.930
So I gave you the
general result just

00:13:34.930 --> 00:13:36.820
to tell you that this
is how you do it.

00:13:36.820 --> 00:13:38.400
But now to understand
it, really,

00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:40.220
let's focus just on two assets.

00:13:40.220 --> 00:13:41.640
OK?

00:13:41.640 --> 00:13:44.160
Suppose we only have
two stocks, a and b.

00:13:44.160 --> 00:13:49.140
And I'm going to calculate the
expected return and standard

00:13:49.140 --> 00:13:52.080
deviation of a portfolio
with just those two stocks.

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:53.730
So the portfolio
weights are going

00:13:53.730 --> 00:13:58.020
to be omega a for stock a,
and omega b for stock b.

00:13:58.020 --> 00:14:00.357
And omega a plus
omega b adds up to 1.

00:14:00.357 --> 00:14:01.440
So just keep that in mind.

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:03.990
I don't put it
there just because I

00:14:03.990 --> 00:14:05.895
want to save a little
space on the slide.

00:14:05.895 --> 00:14:07.770
But these are the weights
for the two stocks.

00:14:07.770 --> 00:14:09.660
And those are the only
two things you hold.

00:14:09.660 --> 00:14:11.070
All right?

00:14:11.070 --> 00:14:12.660
The expected value
is as we said.

00:14:12.660 --> 00:14:14.910
It's a weighted average
of your holdings of

00:14:14.910 --> 00:14:19.350
and b, right, multiplied by the
mean of a and the mean of b.

00:14:19.350 --> 00:14:24.120
Now the variance, the variance
of these two securities

00:14:24.120 --> 00:14:26.430
when they are put
into a portfolio

00:14:26.430 --> 00:14:29.370
is going to be simply
omega a squared

00:14:29.370 --> 00:14:31.820
times the variance
of a plus omega

00:14:31.820 --> 00:14:33.990
b squared times
the variance of b.

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:36.540
And now you only have
one cross product

00:14:36.540 --> 00:14:38.760
to worry about because
you've only got two stocks.

00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:39.540
Right?

00:14:39.540 --> 00:14:44.250
And that is 2 times
omega a times omega

00:14:44.250 --> 00:14:47.580
b times the covariance
between a and b.

00:14:47.580 --> 00:14:50.580
Now you can do this in a 2
by 2 table, just like the n

00:14:50.580 --> 00:14:51.670
by n table.

00:14:51.670 --> 00:14:53.190
And with a 2 by
2 table, you know

00:14:53.190 --> 00:14:57.070
that you've got two diagonal
elements and two off

00:14:57.070 --> 00:14:58.450
diagonal elements.

00:14:58.450 --> 00:15:02.380
And that's where you get
that number 2 for the 2 times

00:15:02.380 --> 00:15:05.950
omega a, omega b
times the covariance.

00:15:05.950 --> 00:15:07.150
OK?

00:15:07.150 --> 00:15:09.910
And I rewrite it in
terms of correlations

00:15:09.910 --> 00:15:13.131
because it's easier to think
in terms of correlations.

00:15:13.131 --> 00:15:13.630
Why?

00:15:13.630 --> 00:15:15.004
Because correlations
we know have

00:15:15.004 --> 00:15:16.950
to be between minus 1 and 1.

00:15:16.950 --> 00:15:20.170
And so if I tell you a stock
has a correlation with another

00:15:20.170 --> 00:15:23.260
of 30%, you can actually
get your arms around that.

00:15:23.260 --> 00:15:24.831
You can get intuition for that.

00:15:24.831 --> 00:15:25.330
All right?

00:15:25.330 --> 00:15:27.310
So it's a little
easier to interpret.

00:15:27.310 --> 00:15:29.440
But either way is fine.

00:15:29.440 --> 00:15:32.620
So we now have an
expression for the mean

00:15:32.620 --> 00:15:35.500
and the variance of a
portfolio of two assets.

00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:38.630
Any questions about this?

00:15:38.630 --> 00:15:40.700
Everybody understand
this and how I got it?

00:15:40.700 --> 00:15:41.790
No tricks up my sleeve.

00:15:41.790 --> 00:15:45.110
It's really meant to be
relatively straightforward.

00:15:45.110 --> 00:15:47.510
But the implications
will be dramatic,

00:15:47.510 --> 00:15:51.030
as I'm going to show
you in a minute.

00:15:51.030 --> 00:15:52.720
OK.

00:15:52.720 --> 00:15:55.516
So let me go through at
least one numerical example.

00:15:55.516 --> 00:15:57.640
And then I'm going to show
you why this is actually

00:15:57.640 --> 00:15:59.380
so important.

00:15:59.380 --> 00:16:03.400
From 1946 to 2001, Motorola
had an average monthly return

00:16:03.400 --> 00:16:09.130
of 1.75%, and a standard
deviation of 9.73%.

00:16:09.130 --> 00:16:12.670
General Motors had an
average return of 1.08%,

00:16:12.670 --> 00:16:16.030
and a standard
deviation of 6.23%.

00:16:16.030 --> 00:16:18.700
That has obviously since
gone up a great deal,

00:16:18.700 --> 00:16:21.010
the standard deviation, that is.

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:26.230
And their correlation
is 0.37, or 37%.

00:16:26.230 --> 00:16:29.590
How would a portfolio of
the two stocks perform?

00:16:29.590 --> 00:16:30.510
Well, it depends.

00:16:30.510 --> 00:16:31.840
What are the weights?

00:16:31.840 --> 00:16:32.685
Right?

00:16:32.685 --> 00:16:34.060
If you change the
weights, you're

00:16:34.060 --> 00:16:35.393
going to change the performance.

00:16:35.393 --> 00:16:36.820
So let's just take a look.

00:16:36.820 --> 00:16:39.940
If you put all your weight
on General Motors and nothing

00:16:39.940 --> 00:16:42.010
on Motorola, not
surprisingly, you're

00:16:42.010 --> 00:16:44.882
going to get General
Motors' return.

00:16:44.882 --> 00:16:47.340
At the other end of the extreme,
if you put all your weight

00:16:47.340 --> 00:16:49.650
on Motorola and nothing
on General Motors,

00:16:49.650 --> 00:16:52.331
you're going to get
Motorola's characteristics.

00:16:52.331 --> 00:16:52.830
All right?

00:16:52.830 --> 00:16:56.050
Nothing mysterious about that.

00:16:56.050 --> 00:17:00.420
However, if you weight the
two, so if you put 50-50

00:17:00.420 --> 00:17:03.390
on General Motors
and Motorola, you're

00:17:03.390 --> 00:17:08.220
going to get a return that is
50-50 of each of those returns.

00:17:08.220 --> 00:17:12.721
But you're going to get
a risk that is not 50-50.

00:17:12.721 --> 00:17:13.220
Right?

00:17:13.220 --> 00:17:16.579
Because the risks,
the risks don't

00:17:16.579 --> 00:17:18.560
aggregate in a linear way.

00:17:18.560 --> 00:17:22.400
The risks actually
aggregate non-linearly

00:17:22.400 --> 00:17:25.520
because of those
covariances or correlations.

00:17:25.520 --> 00:17:26.829
OK.

00:17:26.829 --> 00:17:29.350
So what you see here
is that by taking

00:17:29.350 --> 00:17:32.590
a weighted average of
the two, what you can do

00:17:32.590 --> 00:17:36.970
is you can boost
your return to 1.42%,

00:17:36.970 --> 00:17:40.510
but the extra risk
you're taking is

00:17:40.510 --> 00:17:46.820
from 6.23% to 6.68% per month.

00:17:46.820 --> 00:17:48.880
That's not a big
increase in risk,

00:17:48.880 --> 00:17:53.140
but that is a pretty
significant increase in return.

00:17:53.140 --> 00:17:55.780
Now again, I'm not telling you
that's what you all should do,

00:17:55.780 --> 00:17:57.790
because it depends on
your risk preferences.

00:17:57.790 --> 00:17:59.587
And for the next
lecture or two, I'm

00:17:59.587 --> 00:18:01.420
going to be saying that
over and over again.

00:18:01.420 --> 00:18:03.070
I'm going to be saying
it depends upon your risk

00:18:03.070 --> 00:18:03.580
preferences.

00:18:03.580 --> 00:18:05.999
But at the end of the
next two lectures,

00:18:05.999 --> 00:18:08.290
I'm going to be able to tell
you something that doesn't

00:18:08.290 --> 00:18:09.550
depend on your risk preference.

00:18:09.550 --> 00:18:11.830
I'm going to be able to tell
you something that all of you

00:18:11.830 --> 00:18:13.630
should be willing to
do if you're rational.

00:18:13.630 --> 00:18:16.330
And if you're not, I will
trade with you personally

00:18:16.330 --> 00:18:19.440
to help you learn rationality.

00:18:19.440 --> 00:18:20.440
OK?

00:18:20.440 --> 00:18:22.600
But for now, I
don't have a story

00:18:22.600 --> 00:18:25.540
to tell you about which of
these rows you ought to take.

00:18:25.540 --> 00:18:27.130
There is no ought to here.

00:18:27.130 --> 00:18:30.850
It's just a matter of what you
prefer, risk versus return.

00:18:30.850 --> 00:18:31.960
Right?

00:18:31.960 --> 00:18:34.990
Now interestingly, I
put here one more case

00:18:34.990 --> 00:18:39.640
which lies outside
of the band of 0, 1.

00:18:39.640 --> 00:18:44.020
This is a case where you've
put 125% of your wealth

00:18:44.020 --> 00:18:45.760
into Motorola.

00:18:45.760 --> 00:18:49.570
And you've put negative
25% of your wealth

00:18:49.570 --> 00:18:50.582
into General Motors.

00:18:50.582 --> 00:18:52.790
Remember, we talked about
this in the very beginning.

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:55.660
You're using short
selling to short sell

00:18:55.660 --> 00:18:58.360
General Motors,
which you might think

00:18:58.360 --> 00:19:02.485
is not a bad idea nowadays,
given how troubled they are.

00:19:02.485 --> 00:19:06.730
You're going to short General
Motors, take the proceeds,

00:19:06.730 --> 00:19:09.330
and put that plus the 100%
that you started with,

00:19:09.330 --> 00:19:11.530
you're going to put
that in Motorola.

00:19:11.530 --> 00:19:15.700
So you really want to make
a big bet on communications

00:19:15.700 --> 00:19:18.370
and microprocessors.

00:19:18.370 --> 00:19:19.930
And you're going
to leverage that

00:19:19.930 --> 00:19:23.530
bet by putting a negative
bet on the auto industry.

00:19:23.530 --> 00:19:26.710
That's what that
last row implies.

00:19:26.710 --> 00:19:31.360
And what you get is a
much, much higher rate

00:19:31.360 --> 00:19:35.781
of return than anything
else in the other examples.

00:19:35.781 --> 00:19:36.280
Right?

00:19:36.280 --> 00:19:37.540
Much higher rate of return.

00:19:37.540 --> 00:19:39.430
But look at the risk.

00:19:39.430 --> 00:19:42.132
Now the risk is
close to double what

00:19:42.132 --> 00:19:44.590
you would have gotten had you
put all your money in General

00:19:44.590 --> 00:19:45.089
Motors.

00:19:45.089 --> 00:19:46.930
Are you willing to do that?

00:19:46.930 --> 00:19:48.430
Well, you can
easily imagine there

00:19:48.430 --> 00:19:51.910
are people in this class that
would be delighted to do that,

00:19:51.910 --> 00:19:54.790
and there are others of you
that would be scared to death.

00:19:54.790 --> 00:19:56.480
That's way too much volatility.

00:19:56.480 --> 00:19:58.310
These are monthly
numbers, by the way.

00:19:58.310 --> 00:20:00.760
So if you want to calculate
the annual equivalent,

00:20:00.760 --> 00:20:02.060
how would you do that?

00:20:02.060 --> 00:20:04.480
How would you get an
annual standard deviation

00:20:04.480 --> 00:20:08.530
from a monthly
standard deviation?

00:20:08.530 --> 00:20:11.290
Any idea?

00:20:11.290 --> 00:20:13.270
Well, let's do the return first.

00:20:13.270 --> 00:20:17.860
How do you annualize the monthly
return to get an annual return?

00:20:17.860 --> 00:20:20.350
Let's forget about compounding.

00:20:20.350 --> 00:20:21.340
What would you do?

00:20:21.340 --> 00:20:22.256
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:22.256 --> 00:20:24.040
ANDREW LO: What?

00:20:24.040 --> 00:20:25.059
Multiply by 12.

00:20:25.059 --> 00:20:25.600
That's right.

00:20:25.600 --> 00:20:27.640
If you forget about
confounding, you multiply by 12.

00:20:27.640 --> 00:20:28.890
What if you didn't
forget about compounding?

00:20:28.890 --> 00:20:29.901
Then what do you do?

00:20:29.901 --> 00:20:32.060
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:20:32.060 --> 00:20:34.860
ANDREW LO: Add 1, raise
it to the 12th power,

00:20:34.860 --> 00:20:35.670
then subtract 1.

00:20:35.670 --> 00:20:36.750
That's right.

00:20:36.750 --> 00:20:37.440
OK.

00:20:37.440 --> 00:20:39.770
What about risk?

00:20:39.770 --> 00:20:40.270
Ah, see?

00:20:40.270 --> 00:20:41.200
This is tricky.

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:47.810
What's the variance
of a 12-month return

00:20:47.810 --> 00:20:51.260
in relationship to the
variance of a one-month return?

00:20:51.260 --> 00:20:53.560
We haven't talked about that.

00:20:53.560 --> 00:20:54.760
What is it?

00:20:54.760 --> 00:20:55.700
Yeah?

00:20:55.700 --> 00:20:58.417
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:20:58.417 --> 00:20:59.000
ANDREW LO: No.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:20:59.500
No.

00:20:59.500 --> 00:21:01.670
It doesn't compound in that way.

00:21:01.670 --> 00:21:04.010
Variance is actually
a little simpler,

00:21:04.010 --> 00:21:05.460
under certain assumptions.

00:21:05.460 --> 00:21:06.120
Yeah?

00:21:06.120 --> 00:21:11.332
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:21:11.332 --> 00:21:12.040
ANDREW LO: Right.

00:21:12.040 --> 00:21:14.900
There's no correlation
between one month to the next.

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:19.920
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:21:19.920 --> 00:21:20.920
ANDREW LO: That's right.

00:21:20.920 --> 00:21:21.419
Agreed.

00:21:21.419 --> 00:21:23.980
So let's assume that away.

00:21:23.980 --> 00:21:25.480
Then it's constant.

00:21:25.480 --> 00:21:28.390
But the monthly
variance is constant.

00:21:28.390 --> 00:21:30.250
But what's the annual variance?

00:21:30.250 --> 00:21:32.537
What's the riskiness
of a 12-month return

00:21:32.537 --> 00:21:34.870
if you know what the riskiness
of a one-month return is?

00:21:34.870 --> 00:21:35.506
Yeah?

00:21:35.506 --> 00:21:37.990
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:21:37.990 --> 00:21:40.810
ANDREW LO: Well, it can,
depending on your assumptions.

00:21:40.810 --> 00:21:43.580
But I want a simple
set of assumptions.

00:21:43.580 --> 00:21:44.080
Andy?

00:21:44.080 --> 00:21:46.330
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:21:46.330 --> 00:21:49.060
ANDREW LO: Variance, yes.

00:21:49.060 --> 00:21:50.840
Multiply by 12.

00:21:50.840 --> 00:21:52.130
Now why is that?

00:21:52.130 --> 00:21:53.740
It's because-- and
you know all this.

00:21:53.740 --> 00:21:55.345
You know this from your DMD.

00:21:55.345 --> 00:21:57.490
At least I think you do.

00:21:57.490 --> 00:21:59.770
You may not think
you do, but you do.

00:21:59.770 --> 00:22:04.000
The variance of a plus
b is equal to what?

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:05.680
Who can tell me?

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:07.390
What's the variance of a plus b?

00:22:07.390 --> 00:22:08.470
Two random variables.

00:22:12.930 --> 00:22:18.930
Variance of a plus
variance of b plus 2 times

00:22:18.930 --> 00:22:20.310
the covariance of a and b.

00:22:20.310 --> 00:22:23.824
If the covariance is 0,
then it is the variance

00:22:23.824 --> 00:22:24.990
of a plus the variance of b.

00:22:24.990 --> 00:22:26.700
Absolutely, that's right.

00:22:26.700 --> 00:22:29.070
So if we assume
there are no cycles,

00:22:29.070 --> 00:22:31.680
there are no predictabilities,
there's no regularities,

00:22:31.680 --> 00:22:33.540
there's no correlation,
every month

00:22:33.540 --> 00:22:35.560
is independent of
every other month,

00:22:35.560 --> 00:22:39.630
than the variance
of a 12-month return

00:22:39.630 --> 00:22:43.680
is literally just 12 times the
variance of a one-month return,

00:22:43.680 --> 00:22:46.650
assuming the variances stay
constant throughout the month.

00:22:46.650 --> 00:22:49.270
The monthly variance
doesn't go up or down.

00:22:49.270 --> 00:22:50.740
OK?

00:22:50.740 --> 00:22:51.784
Now, that's the variance.

00:22:51.784 --> 00:22:53.200
What about the
standard deviation?

00:22:53.200 --> 00:22:55.674
The standard deviation is the
square root of the variance.

00:22:55.674 --> 00:22:58.090
So that means that the standard
deviation on an annualized

00:22:58.090 --> 00:23:03.840
basis is equal to square root of
12 times the standard deviation

00:23:03.840 --> 00:23:04.420
of a monthly.

00:23:04.420 --> 00:23:04.920
OK.

00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:06.390
So finally, we're almost there.

00:23:06.390 --> 00:23:08.070
What's the square root of 12?

00:23:08.070 --> 00:23:11.760
Something between
3 and 4, right?

00:23:11.760 --> 00:23:15.180
So I don't know, call
it 3 and 1/2, whatever.

00:23:15.180 --> 00:23:20.850
We have to take this number and
multiply it by about 3 and 1/2.

00:23:20.850 --> 00:23:23.220
And that will get us an
approximate annual standard

00:23:23.220 --> 00:23:24.370
deviation.

00:23:24.370 --> 00:23:27.600
So a 12% volatility
multiplied by 3 and 1/2,

00:23:27.600 --> 00:23:31.650
you're talking about some crazy
volatile stock, or portfolio.

00:23:31.650 --> 00:23:33.277
But actually,
nowadays, you know,

00:23:33.277 --> 00:23:34.860
we're used to that
kind of volatility.

00:23:34.860 --> 00:23:36.310
That's no big deal.

00:23:36.310 --> 00:23:39.090
But relative to the
individual stock,

00:23:39.090 --> 00:23:40.830
it's quite a bit more volatile.

00:23:40.830 --> 00:23:42.300
OK?

00:23:42.300 --> 00:23:45.120
So this is an example
of how you compute

00:23:45.120 --> 00:23:50.160
the riskiness and the return
of a portfolio of two stocks.

00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:53.979
And when you do this, you get
a whole bunch of possibilities.

00:23:53.979 --> 00:23:55.770
And the idea behind
modern portfolio theory

00:23:55.770 --> 00:23:58.760
is you pick the one
that you like the best.

00:23:58.760 --> 00:24:00.320
And that's optimal for you.

00:24:03.480 --> 00:24:10.500
Now let me graph this in that
mean-standard deviation graph,

00:24:10.500 --> 00:24:14.020
and you'll see something
really interesting.

00:24:14.020 --> 00:24:19.550
So here's General Motors
and there is Motorola.

00:24:19.550 --> 00:24:22.520
And what I've graphed
with the red dots

00:24:22.520 --> 00:24:26.570
is just the different
combinations of 25/75,

00:24:26.570 --> 00:24:30.820
50/50, 75/25, and so on.

00:24:30.820 --> 00:24:35.860
And so the red dots that are
strictly between 0 and 1,

00:24:35.860 --> 00:24:38.830
where the weights are between
0 and 1, those are the dots

00:24:38.830 --> 00:24:44.566
contained in that arc
between GM and Motorola.

00:24:44.566 --> 00:24:45.940
So the first point
I want to make

00:24:45.940 --> 00:24:52.370
is that when you graph
the risk/reward trade-off,

00:24:52.370 --> 00:24:55.430
as I told you, it's not linear.

00:24:55.430 --> 00:24:56.540
It's non-linear.

00:24:56.540 --> 00:24:58.470
In fact, it's curved.

00:24:58.470 --> 00:25:00.950
It looks like a bullet.

00:25:00.950 --> 00:25:01.450
OK?

00:25:04.870 --> 00:25:06.670
That tells you right
away that there's

00:25:06.670 --> 00:25:09.970
something more subtle
about portfolio theory

00:25:09.970 --> 00:25:12.370
than just taking
weighted averages.

00:25:12.370 --> 00:25:17.620
The means are weighted
averages, but the variances

00:25:17.620 --> 00:25:21.027
are not because of the
covariance between them.

00:25:21.027 --> 00:25:22.610
And then when you
take the square root

00:25:22.610 --> 00:25:26.200
to get the standard deviation,
it looks a little bit more

00:25:26.200 --> 00:25:29.120
complicated, yet again.

00:25:29.120 --> 00:25:30.920
It looks like this.

00:25:30.920 --> 00:25:35.570
Now that red dot that
goes beyond Motorola,

00:25:35.570 --> 00:25:39.500
that red dot is the case where
you're shorting General Motors

00:25:39.500 --> 00:25:44.290
and you're using the proceeds
to take an extra large position

00:25:44.290 --> 00:25:45.350
in Motorola.

00:25:45.350 --> 00:25:46.490
OK?

00:25:46.490 --> 00:25:52.869
So you're going beyond the
Motorola risk/reward point.

00:25:52.869 --> 00:25:54.660
So I need you to spend
a little bit of time

00:25:54.660 --> 00:25:57.990
now twisting your
brain in a way that

00:25:57.990 --> 00:26:00.700
makes this more understandable.

00:26:00.700 --> 00:26:04.420
What I mean by that
is that you have

00:26:04.420 --> 00:26:07.330
to think about the weights
of the various different

00:26:07.330 --> 00:26:08.380
portfolios.

00:26:08.380 --> 00:26:11.050
But the weights don't
show up on this graph.

00:26:11.050 --> 00:26:12.550
But I want you to
keep those weights

