00:39:18.550 --> 00:39:22.600
I'm going to get
this becoming 1,

00:39:22.600 --> 00:39:24.760
and then I'll get
another simplification

00:39:24.760 --> 00:39:26.650
of this expression.

00:39:26.650 --> 00:39:30.130
And similarly, if I assume that
the correlation is minus 1,

00:39:30.130 --> 00:39:32.680
then I'm going to get yet
another simplification

00:39:32.680 --> 00:39:33.520
of this expression.

00:39:33.520 --> 00:39:35.930
It's an algebra that I'll
show you in a minute.

00:39:35.930 --> 00:39:38.410
But this is what I'm doing
in these three columns.

00:39:38.410 --> 00:39:41.260
I'm assuming different values
of correlation between General

00:39:41.260 --> 00:39:44.410
Motors and Motorola,
and then computing

00:39:44.410 --> 00:39:47.390
the standard deviation of the
portfolio using this formula.

00:39:47.390 --> 00:39:47.890
OK?

00:39:47.890 --> 00:39:51.130
So you can all do this at
home, do this in a spreadsheet.

00:39:51.130 --> 00:39:55.650
It's going to be very
easy to check my work.

00:39:55.650 --> 00:39:58.570
But I want to show you the
graph because that's really,

00:39:58.570 --> 00:40:02.530
I think, the insightful
intuition here.

00:40:02.530 --> 00:40:04.250
Look at the graphs.

00:40:04.250 --> 00:40:08.410
These are the graphs of
the three different cases

00:40:08.410 --> 00:40:13.210
of zero correlation,
perfect correlation,

00:40:13.210 --> 00:40:15.820
and perfect negative
correlation.

00:40:15.820 --> 00:40:17.830
I want to go to each
one of these with you.

00:40:17.830 --> 00:40:20.710
So the case of perfect
positive correlation,

00:40:20.710 --> 00:40:25.000
it turns out that the
risk/reward trade off is

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:27.410
actually just a straight line.

00:40:27.410 --> 00:40:29.230
It gets really, really simple.

00:40:29.230 --> 00:40:31.350
It's just a straight line.

00:40:31.350 --> 00:40:35.089
So in particular, there
is no non-linearity.

00:40:35.089 --> 00:40:37.380
Because if they're perfectly
correlated, you know what?

00:40:37.380 --> 00:40:40.182
You basically have
virtually the same stock.

00:40:40.182 --> 00:40:41.640
The only difference
is that they're

00:40:41.640 --> 00:40:43.180
different scales of each other.

00:40:43.180 --> 00:40:43.950
Right?

00:40:43.950 --> 00:40:45.706
But if they're
perfectly correlated,

00:40:45.706 --> 00:40:48.330
that means that there's a linear
relationship between those two

00:40:48.330 --> 00:40:49.320
stocks.

00:40:49.320 --> 00:40:52.820
And so when you do this
mean variance analysis,

00:40:52.820 --> 00:40:54.900
in mean variance
space, you basically

00:40:54.900 --> 00:40:58.790
get no nonlinear-- you
don't get that little bump,

00:40:58.790 --> 00:41:01.470
the little bullet
that we saw before.

00:41:01.470 --> 00:41:01.970
Right?

00:41:01.970 --> 00:41:05.580
So there's no way you can get
less risk than General Motors

00:41:05.580 --> 00:41:08.580
unless you end up shorting
Motorola and putting it

00:41:08.580 --> 00:41:09.330
in General Motors.

00:41:09.330 --> 00:41:13.350
And then your expected
return goes down,

00:41:13.350 --> 00:41:15.941
as well as your risk.

00:41:15.941 --> 00:41:16.440
All right.

00:41:16.440 --> 00:41:22.040
Now let's take the case where
you've got no correlation.

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:24.590
It turns out that if
you have no correlation,

00:41:24.590 --> 00:41:26.870
you get the bullet.

00:41:26.870 --> 00:41:31.430
But the bullet is even
more wedge shaped.

00:41:31.430 --> 00:41:34.970
What that means is that you
can reduce even more risk

00:41:34.970 --> 00:41:36.220
without getting rid of return.

00:41:36.220 --> 00:41:39.080
Remember the red dot that we
saw in the previous slide?

00:41:39.080 --> 00:41:40.190
This red dot?

00:41:40.190 --> 00:41:43.710
Well, in the case where
you've got 0 correlation--

00:41:43.710 --> 00:41:46.980
this is the case where the
correlation is 0.37, 37%.

00:41:46.980 --> 00:41:47.480
Right?

00:41:47.480 --> 00:41:48.980
That's what the data tells us.

00:41:48.980 --> 00:41:52.000
But if you assume that
the correlation was zero,

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:56.900
you would get even more
of a savings of volatility

00:41:56.900 --> 00:41:59.100
for a given level
of expected return.

00:41:59.100 --> 00:41:59.600
OK?

00:41:59.600 --> 00:42:01.310
So it would look like this.

00:42:01.310 --> 00:42:02.840
You see how this
bullet sticks out

00:42:02.840 --> 00:42:05.210
a lot more than the
previous red dot that

00:42:05.210 --> 00:42:07.070
was somewhere over here?

00:42:07.070 --> 00:42:09.220
OK?

00:42:09.220 --> 00:42:11.170
Now let's continue.

00:42:11.170 --> 00:42:14.560
Suppose the correlation
is minus 50%.

00:42:14.560 --> 00:42:19.600
Then you get an
even wider bullet,

00:42:19.600 --> 00:42:23.110
that sticks out even
more, that saves you

00:42:23.110 --> 00:42:24.310
more standard deviation.

00:42:24.310 --> 00:42:26.690
You're getting to
the west even more.

00:42:26.690 --> 00:42:30.110
And finally, and here is where
you get a really remarkable

00:42:30.110 --> 00:42:36.700
result. If the
correlation is minus 100%,

00:42:36.700 --> 00:42:38.310
you know what you get?

00:42:38.310 --> 00:42:41.510
You get a piecewise
linear trade off.

00:42:41.510 --> 00:42:46.060
You get this and that.

00:42:46.060 --> 00:42:48.100
It doesn't turn into a wedge.

00:42:48.100 --> 00:42:52.630
It turns into a triangle that
actually hits the x-axis.

00:42:52.630 --> 00:42:54.850
And the reason this is
such a startling result

00:42:54.850 --> 00:42:58.030
is it tells us that
there exists a way

00:42:58.030 --> 00:43:02.710
to construct a portfolio that
gives us a rate of return

00:43:02.710 --> 00:43:09.410
of like 1.39% with no risk.

00:43:09.410 --> 00:43:12.920
Zero risk.

00:43:12.920 --> 00:43:14.390
1.39%.

00:43:14.390 --> 00:43:18.200
Let's just call it 1.3%
to be conservative.

00:43:18.200 --> 00:43:21.530
Multiply that by
12 and you're going

00:43:21.530 --> 00:43:23.600
to get something like what?

00:43:23.600 --> 00:43:26.980
16% a year?

00:43:26.980 --> 00:43:29.950
You tell me if you know of any
investment opportunities that

00:43:29.950 --> 00:43:33.490
gives you a return of
16% a year with no risk,

00:43:33.490 --> 00:43:36.070
and I'll examine that
for you carefully.

00:43:36.070 --> 00:43:38.290
OK?

00:43:38.290 --> 00:43:40.480
It doesn't exist, of course.

00:43:40.480 --> 00:43:42.250
The reason it doesn't
exist is because you

00:43:42.250 --> 00:43:48.860
can't find two assets that have
perfect negative correlation.

00:43:48.860 --> 00:43:51.890
If you could, there
are wondrous things

00:43:51.890 --> 00:43:55.310
you could achieve
with that combination.

00:43:55.310 --> 00:43:58.400
And portfolio theory
basically tells us how, right?

00:43:58.400 --> 00:44:03.930
This is a recipe book for
how to exploit correlation.

00:44:03.930 --> 00:44:04.430
All right?

00:44:04.430 --> 00:44:07.040
Now again, I can't
tell you where

00:44:07.040 --> 00:44:09.110
you should be on
this curve other

00:44:09.110 --> 00:44:13.030
than if it's really minus
1, then I would be here.

00:44:13.030 --> 00:44:13.790
OK?

00:44:13.790 --> 00:44:16.020
Lots of return, no risk.

00:44:16.020 --> 00:44:17.990
That's an arbitrage.

00:44:17.990 --> 00:44:19.780
We know that that
can't possibly happen.

00:44:19.780 --> 00:44:20.696
There's no free lunch.

00:44:20.696 --> 00:44:24.650
There's no arbitrage, on
average, over circumstances.

00:44:24.650 --> 00:44:28.220
However, if the
bullet is minus 0.5,

00:44:28.220 --> 00:44:30.890
then you've got
lots of opportunity

00:44:30.890 --> 00:44:35.240
to create really attractive
portfolios that doesn't require

00:44:35.240 --> 00:44:36.890
Warren Buffett's skills.

00:44:36.890 --> 00:44:38.431
There's no forecasting here.

00:44:38.431 --> 00:44:38.930
Right?

00:44:38.930 --> 00:44:40.264
We're not trying to pick stocks.

00:44:40.264 --> 00:44:42.180
We're not trying to see
how the market's going

00:44:42.180 --> 00:44:43.070
to do next month.

00:44:43.070 --> 00:44:44.540
Who knows?

00:44:44.540 --> 00:44:47.480
All we're assuming is
that means and variances

00:44:47.480 --> 00:44:50.990
are stable over time,
and the correlation

00:44:50.990 --> 00:44:51.980
is stable over time.

00:44:51.980 --> 00:44:55.070
Those are nontrivial
assumptions, I grant you.

00:44:55.070 --> 00:44:56.750
But if you believe
in those assumptions

00:44:56.750 --> 00:44:58.700
more than you believe
in your ability

00:44:58.700 --> 00:45:01.100
to forecast what's going
to happen to General Motors

00:45:01.100 --> 00:45:03.710
six months from now, then
this might be a good way

00:45:03.710 --> 00:45:05.330
to construct a portfolio.

00:45:05.330 --> 00:45:07.970
But I haven't told you where
on this curve you ought to be.

00:45:07.970 --> 00:45:10.620
I just told you how to
construct that curve.

00:45:10.620 --> 00:45:11.120
All right?

00:45:11.120 --> 00:45:13.310
It's your job to look
at the curve and say,

00:45:13.310 --> 00:45:16.080
I like this point,
or I like that point,

00:45:16.080 --> 00:45:18.230
based upon your own
personal preferences

00:45:18.230 --> 00:45:19.640
for risk and reward.

00:45:19.640 --> 00:45:23.180
So we're not there yet where
I can tell you how to behave.

00:45:23.180 --> 00:45:25.750
I will get there in about
a lecture and a half.

00:45:25.750 --> 00:45:27.890
But we've got to build
up the infrastructure

00:45:27.890 --> 00:45:29.420
to be able to get us there.

00:45:29.420 --> 00:45:30.170
OK.

00:45:30.170 --> 00:45:32.180
So what this tells
us is that we need

00:45:32.180 --> 00:45:35.420
to know what the correlation
is in order to figure out

00:45:35.420 --> 00:45:38.600
where we are going to be on
these different curves, which

00:45:38.600 --> 00:45:40.760
curve is going to apply.

00:45:40.760 --> 00:45:43.220
When you have lots
of correlation,

00:45:43.220 --> 00:45:46.670
a correlation of 1, there
really isn't much of a risk

00:45:46.670 --> 00:45:49.280
savings per unit return.

00:45:49.280 --> 00:45:53.960
We can't get a lower risk
for a given level of return.

00:45:53.960 --> 00:45:59.660
But we can if there is less
correlation than perfect.

00:45:59.660 --> 00:46:03.680
And these are the different
curves that illustrate that.

00:46:03.680 --> 00:46:05.180
OK.

00:46:05.180 --> 00:46:07.940
So there are some other
examples that I'd like you

00:46:07.940 --> 00:46:09.450
to work through on your own.

00:46:09.450 --> 00:46:11.390
This is another
portfolio calculation.

00:46:11.390 --> 00:46:14.690
Just go through the same
calculations that we did here.

00:46:14.690 --> 00:46:17.510
And you know, you'll graph the
different risk/reward trade off

00:46:17.510 --> 00:46:20.120
between these two, General
Dynamics and Motorola.

00:46:20.120 --> 00:46:22.580
And you can get exactly
the same analysis

00:46:22.580 --> 00:46:26.450
with those two stocks,
General Dynamics and Motorola.

00:46:26.450 --> 00:46:29.200
OK?

00:46:29.200 --> 00:46:33.080
Now what about if you
got a risk free rate?

00:46:33.080 --> 00:46:36.760
So suppose that the two
assets that I want to look at

00:46:36.760 --> 00:46:40.750
is not General Motors and
Motorola, but rather the stock

00:46:40.750 --> 00:46:44.700
market and treasury bills.

00:46:44.700 --> 00:46:47.710
Then what does your risk/reward
trade off look like?

00:46:47.710 --> 00:46:51.180
Well, it turns out that in the
case where treasury bills are

00:46:51.180 --> 00:46:57.070
in question, the volatility
of treasury bills

00:46:57.070 --> 00:46:59.260
is virtually zero.

00:46:59.260 --> 00:47:01.420
It's not exactly
zero because there

00:47:01.420 --> 00:47:04.450
may be some kind of randomness
in the underlying rates

00:47:04.450 --> 00:47:07.000
of return because of
inflationary expectations.

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:11.050
But as an approximation,
if it's a risk free rate

00:47:11.050 --> 00:47:13.780
and you know that you're going
to get that risk free rate,

00:47:13.780 --> 00:47:16.450
then the volatility
of that return

00:47:16.450 --> 00:47:19.940
is in fact 0 over
that period of time.

00:47:19.940 --> 00:47:23.860
So in that case, the expected
rate of return of a portfolio

00:47:23.860 --> 00:47:25.990
between the stock
market and T-bills,

00:47:25.990 --> 00:47:27.520
that's the weighted average.

00:47:27.520 --> 00:47:31.300
But the variance is going to
be very simple because it's

00:47:31.300 --> 00:47:34.150
going to be the variance
of 1, which is 0,

00:47:34.150 --> 00:47:36.850
plus the variance
of the other, plus 2

00:47:36.850 --> 00:47:41.260
times the weighted average
times the covariance.

00:47:41.260 --> 00:47:42.560
But there is no covariance.

00:47:42.560 --> 00:47:43.060
Right?

00:47:43.060 --> 00:47:45.250
There's no correlation
because one of the things

00:47:45.250 --> 00:47:47.290
is non-random.

00:47:47.290 --> 00:47:51.670
And so when you work out
the weights for the two

00:47:51.670 --> 00:47:55.846
and you graph
them, you get this.

00:47:55.846 --> 00:48:00.860
This is a beautiful thing, nice
and simple, no weird curves

00:48:00.860 --> 00:48:03.320
or any kind of bullet shape.

00:48:03.320 --> 00:48:05.370
You've got T-bills here.

00:48:05.370 --> 00:48:07.460
You've got the
stock market here.

00:48:07.460 --> 00:48:10.640
And the weights,
as you vary them,

00:48:10.640 --> 00:48:15.740
will bring you anywhere
along this line or possibly

00:48:15.740 --> 00:48:17.090
up over here.

00:48:17.090 --> 00:48:19.820
If you're in the middle of
this line-- so literally,

00:48:19.820 --> 00:48:24.770
if you have the same distance
between here and here and here

00:48:24.770 --> 00:48:25.760
and here--

00:48:25.760 --> 00:48:28.400
that actually gives
you a 50-50 weighting

00:48:28.400 --> 00:48:30.980
on those portfolio weights.

00:48:30.980 --> 00:48:34.370
So geometrically, this
actually corresponds

00:48:34.370 --> 00:48:40.070
to a 50-50 weighting of
T-bills and the S&amp;P. OK?

00:48:40.070 --> 00:48:43.940
Now question, what happens
when you are over here?

00:48:43.940 --> 00:48:45.710
Let's suppose you're
at this point.

00:48:45.710 --> 00:48:48.350
At this point, what would your
portfolio weights look like?

00:48:48.350 --> 00:48:51.490
How would you characterize that?

00:48:51.490 --> 00:48:52.170
Yeah, Brian?

00:48:52.170 --> 00:48:56.190
AUDIENCE: Short T-bills to
buy into the stock market?

00:48:56.190 --> 00:48:57.190
ANDREW LO: That's right.

00:48:57.190 --> 00:48:57.970
Short T-bills.

00:48:57.970 --> 00:49:01.510
What does it mean
to short T-bills?

00:49:01.510 --> 00:49:03.380
What are you doing?

00:49:03.380 --> 00:49:04.482
You're borrowing.

00:49:04.482 --> 00:49:05.440
You're borrowing money.

00:49:05.440 --> 00:49:06.700
You're leveraging.

00:49:06.700 --> 00:49:08.530
When you're shorting
T-bills, you're

00:49:08.530 --> 00:49:10.860
basically borrowing and
getting cash upfront

00:49:10.860 --> 00:49:13.670
you're to pay back
later with interest.

00:49:13.670 --> 00:49:16.390
So shorting T-bills
is just borrowing.

00:49:16.390 --> 00:49:18.880
If you're borrowing money
and you're putting it

00:49:18.880 --> 00:49:21.580
into the stock market in
addition to 100% of your own

00:49:21.580 --> 00:49:23.990
wealth-- you've borrowed
additional money to put it

00:49:23.990 --> 00:49:24.911
in the stock market--

00:49:24.911 --> 00:49:26.410
then you're going
to be way up here.

00:49:26.410 --> 00:49:31.360
Higher return, much higher
up here than down here,

00:49:31.360 --> 00:49:33.710
but you're going to get
higher risk, as well.

00:49:33.710 --> 00:49:38.270
So leverage, this idea
of borrowing and putting

00:49:38.270 --> 00:49:41.450
your money in the stock
market, that increases

00:49:41.450 --> 00:49:43.850
your expected rate of return.

00:49:43.850 --> 00:49:45.980
But it also increases your risk.

00:49:45.980 --> 00:49:47.210
OK?

00:49:47.210 --> 00:49:49.575
Leverage increases your risk.

00:49:49.575 --> 00:49:51.950
And now getting back to the
question that Lewis asked us,

00:49:51.950 --> 00:49:53.600
is this where we
got into trouble

00:49:53.600 --> 00:49:54.680
with the current crisis?

00:49:54.680 --> 00:49:56.850
Yes, in a nutshell it is.

00:49:56.850 --> 00:49:58.850
But it's more complicated
because the underlying

00:49:58.850 --> 00:50:00.530
securities are more complex.

00:50:00.530 --> 00:50:04.160
But the basic idea is
if you leverage up,

00:50:04.160 --> 00:50:06.590
if you leverage
up, way up here--

00:50:06.590 --> 00:50:08.570
you're up maybe out there--

00:50:08.570 --> 00:50:11.756
and all of a sudden
there's a bump in the road

00:50:11.756 --> 00:50:13.880
and what you are leveraging,
this thing that you're

00:50:13.880 --> 00:50:19.550
investing in is not nearly
as smooth and as riskless

00:50:19.550 --> 00:50:23.760
as you thought it was,
it could wipe you out.

00:50:23.760 --> 00:50:29.100
And one of those elements that
could cause such a wipeout

00:50:29.100 --> 00:50:32.550
is if you somehow
forgot about the fact

00:50:32.550 --> 00:50:35.350
that correlations can change.

00:50:35.350 --> 00:50:39.810
So you thought that you were,
I don't know, somewhere here,

00:50:39.810 --> 00:50:43.380
and all of a sudden
correlations go to 1

00:50:43.380 --> 00:50:45.700
and now you're
actually over here.

00:50:45.700 --> 00:50:47.940
You see how risk can
change really quickly?

00:50:47.940 --> 00:50:51.790
Correlations don't have
to be stable over time.

00:50:51.790 --> 00:50:55.099
And that's the lesson that
most people in industry,

00:50:55.099 --> 00:50:57.390
who don't have a finance
background, who've never taken

00:50:57.390 --> 00:50:59.880
this course, they won't know.

00:50:59.880 --> 00:51:01.590
These are physicists
or mathematicians

00:51:01.590 --> 00:51:02.370
or computer scientists.

00:51:02.370 --> 00:51:03.490
They estimate the correlation.

00:51:03.490 --> 00:51:05.580
It's a parameter, like
the gravitational constant

00:51:05.580 --> 00:51:06.690
or Avogadro's number.

00:51:06.690 --> 00:51:08.350
Let's plug it in.

00:51:08.350 --> 00:51:12.630
Hey, 9.08 times 10 the 23rd,
that's what it should be.

00:51:12.630 --> 00:51:16.650
And nobody ever told them
that it could change.

00:51:16.650 --> 00:51:20.820
And when it changes, bad things
can happen really quickly.

00:51:20.820 --> 00:51:22.320
So we're going to
come back to that.

00:51:22.320 --> 00:51:24.347
But let's get the standard
theory down first,

00:51:24.347 --> 00:51:26.180
and then we'll talk a
bit about application.

