This bullet point
here says that you're

00:51:57.690 --> 00:52:00.190
going to be at
approximately, something--

00:52:00.190 --> 00:52:02.370
if the correlation-- let's
be realistic about it.

00:52:02.370 --> 00:52:02.520
OK?

00:52:02.520 --> 00:52:04.440
The correlation is not
going to be minus 0.5.

00:52:04.440 --> 00:52:06.690
It's going to be more like 0.37.

00:52:06.690 --> 00:52:09.530
So this bullet here is
going to be like 1--

00:52:09.530 --> 00:52:12.570
I don't know, let's call it
1.3% just to make it easy.

00:52:12.570 --> 00:52:14.760
And you've got a standard
deviation of about 6%.

00:52:14.760 --> 00:52:15.390
OK?

00:52:15.390 --> 00:52:17.010
So on an annualized
basis, that's

00:52:17.010 --> 00:52:22.740
giving you a return, 1.3 times
12 is something like what, 16%?

00:52:22.740 --> 00:52:27.600
16% return, but the risk on
an annualized basis multiplied

00:52:27.600 --> 00:52:29.790
by 3 and 1/2 is
about, let's say 20%.

00:52:29.790 --> 00:52:32.940
So 20%, 22% annual
standard deviation

00:52:32.940 --> 00:52:36.470
for a 16% rate of return.

00:52:36.470 --> 00:52:38.290
Now some of you might like that.

00:52:38.290 --> 00:52:41.680
But I have a few
friends here for whom

00:52:41.680 --> 00:52:44.546
that return is just boring.

00:52:44.546 --> 00:52:46.420
That's just not going
to get their attention.

00:52:46.420 --> 00:52:48.520
What they want is they
want to be up here,

00:52:48.520 --> 00:52:50.680
you know, like at
2% rate of return.

00:52:50.680 --> 00:52:54.350
2% rate of return per
month is about 24% a year.

00:52:54.350 --> 00:52:55.840
So if you're a
hedge fund manager,

00:52:55.840 --> 00:52:58.570
24% is when you start
to begin to feel alive.

00:52:58.570 --> 00:52:59.290
You know?

00:52:59.290 --> 00:53:01.660
That's when things really
start to happen for you.

00:53:01.660 --> 00:53:05.080
And at 24% annual
return, you can't

00:53:05.080 --> 00:53:07.464
have volatility
of like 15% or 20%

00:53:07.464 --> 00:53:08.880
unless you're doing
something, you

00:53:08.880 --> 00:53:12.970
know, really different than
the standard market portfolio.

00:53:12.970 --> 00:53:15.760
So a hedge fund manager is going
to say, Anon, give me a break.

00:53:15.760 --> 00:53:17.551
You know, this is going
to put me to sleep.

00:53:17.551 --> 00:53:18.520
I want to be up here.

00:53:18.520 --> 00:53:20.470
But you know, you've got
a family, three kids,

00:53:20.470 --> 00:53:23.290
you have to worry about
making mortgage payments.

00:53:23.290 --> 00:53:25.720
That kind of lifestyle
is not for you.

00:53:25.720 --> 00:53:28.630
So in both cases,
though, in both cases,

00:53:28.630 --> 00:53:33.290
we can agree that where we want
to be is on this curve, right?

00:53:33.290 --> 00:53:37.810
In other words, you would never
want to be here, at this point.

00:53:37.810 --> 00:53:38.500
Why?

00:53:38.500 --> 00:53:41.140
Because if you were
here, you can either,

00:53:41.140 --> 00:53:43.830
for the same level of
risk, increase your return.

00:53:43.830 --> 00:53:47.100
Or for the same level of
return, decrease your risk.

00:53:47.100 --> 00:53:50.540
So what we can agree
on, even though we

00:53:50.540 --> 00:53:53.450
don't agree on where we
want to be on that curve,

00:53:53.450 --> 00:53:56.750
we can all agree we want to
be on that curve as opposed

00:53:56.750 --> 00:53:57.890
to inside the curve.

00:53:57.890 --> 00:53:58.625
Right?

00:53:58.625 --> 00:54:00.110
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:54:00.110 --> 00:54:00.920
ANDREW LO: Exactly.

00:54:00.920 --> 00:54:01.679
Great point.

00:54:01.679 --> 00:54:03.470
Why would we want to
be on the bottom half?

00:54:03.470 --> 00:54:04.610
Nobody would want to do that.

00:54:04.610 --> 00:54:06.090
Because if were on
the bottom half,

00:54:06.090 --> 00:54:08.465
you can just as easily
move up to the top,

00:54:08.465 --> 00:54:10.340
and you have a higher
expected rate of return

00:54:10.340 --> 00:54:11.741
for the same level of risk.

00:54:11.741 --> 00:54:12.740
So you're exactly right.

00:54:12.740 --> 00:54:15.590
That bottom half of the curve,
you can just throw it away.

00:54:15.590 --> 00:54:16.452
All right?

00:54:16.452 --> 00:54:18.410
The only people that are
going to be down there

00:54:18.410 --> 00:54:19.600
are knuckleheads.

00:54:19.600 --> 00:54:20.600
All right?

00:54:20.600 --> 00:54:22.520
So we don't want
to be down there.

00:54:22.520 --> 00:54:25.280
So in fact, the only part of
the curve that really matters

00:54:25.280 --> 00:54:28.400
is this point, going
all the way up.

00:54:28.400 --> 00:54:30.680
And we're going to give a
name to that in a minute.

00:54:30.680 --> 00:54:35.469
That's going to be called the
efficient frontier because you

00:54:35.469 --> 00:54:37.010
would never want to
do anything else.

00:54:37.010 --> 00:54:39.270
Actually, that's not quite true.

00:54:39.270 --> 00:54:44.450
What everybody would like to do
is they'd like to be up here.

00:54:44.450 --> 00:54:47.740
Unfortunately, we
can't get there.

00:54:47.740 --> 00:54:51.970
We can't get there with just
General Motors and Motorola.

00:54:51.970 --> 00:54:53.860
In a few minutes,
I'm going to show you

00:54:53.860 --> 00:54:57.250
how you might be able to
get there with other stocks.

00:54:57.250 --> 00:54:59.590
If you introduce
other assets, then you

00:54:59.590 --> 00:55:00.820
might be able to get there.

00:55:00.820 --> 00:55:03.190
But you can't get
there right now.

00:55:03.190 --> 00:55:04.360
OK.

00:55:04.360 --> 00:55:09.280
So here we are with
stocks and T-bills.

00:55:09.280 --> 00:55:14.690
And we know that we'll get
the linear combination here.

00:55:14.690 --> 00:55:17.720
What I'd like to do next is to
make this yet more complicated.

00:55:17.720 --> 00:55:18.220
All right?

00:55:18.220 --> 00:55:20.050
And before I do, let
me just summarize

00:55:20.050 --> 00:55:21.640
what we've done so far.

00:55:21.640 --> 00:55:24.490
What we've done is to
show that with two assets,

00:55:24.490 --> 00:55:27.280
we can do all of
this analytically,

00:55:27.280 --> 00:55:31.330
and illustrate graphically,
all of the intuition that holds

00:55:31.330 --> 00:55:33.460
for the more general case.

00:55:33.460 --> 00:55:35.910
With two assets, the
expected rate of return

00:55:35.910 --> 00:55:37.870
is just a simple
weighted average.

00:55:37.870 --> 00:55:40.870
But the variance is not just
a simple weighted average.

00:55:40.870 --> 00:55:43.480
It's more complicated and
it depends, in particular,

00:55:43.480 --> 00:55:44.830
on the correlation.

00:55:44.830 --> 00:55:47.590
For different correlations,
we get different shapes

00:55:47.590 --> 00:55:50.260
of trade offs in
mean-variance space.

00:55:50.260 --> 00:55:53.320
And you have to understand
what those trade offs are.

00:55:53.320 --> 00:55:55.840
If it turns out that one of
the two assets is T-bills,

00:55:55.840 --> 00:55:58.990
for example, then the trade
off is really straight line.

00:55:58.990 --> 00:55:59.740
OK?

00:55:59.740 --> 00:56:02.320
But if both assets
are risky, then you

00:56:02.320 --> 00:56:06.940
get the bullet shape until
you either get minus 1 or 1

00:56:06.940 --> 00:56:08.020
in terms of correlations.

00:56:08.020 --> 00:56:11.350
And then you get straight
lines of different stripes

00:56:11.350 --> 00:56:12.950
in those two different cases.

00:56:12.950 --> 00:56:13.450
OK.

00:56:13.450 --> 00:56:15.670
Now we're ready to talk
about the general case.

00:56:15.670 --> 00:56:19.630
The general case works exactly
the same as the two asset case.

00:56:19.630 --> 00:56:21.460
You've got your means.

00:56:21.460 --> 00:56:22.840
You've got your variances.

00:56:22.840 --> 00:56:24.580
And you've got your covariances.

00:56:24.580 --> 00:56:27.040
And you add up all of
these different covariances

00:56:27.040 --> 00:56:30.050
to get the total variance
of the portfolio.

00:56:30.050 --> 00:56:35.480
And if you consider a
couple of simple cases,

00:56:35.480 --> 00:56:38.520
like for example, an
equal weighted portfolio--

00:56:38.520 --> 00:56:43.670
so you've got n assets
and you put each of your--

00:56:43.670 --> 00:56:46.670
for each of your assets, you
put 1 over n of your wealth

00:56:46.670 --> 00:56:47.750
in them.

00:56:47.750 --> 00:56:50.090
Then you can show
that the variance

00:56:50.090 --> 00:56:55.730
of your entire portfolio is
equal to the average variance

00:56:55.730 --> 00:57:01.940
plus n times n minus 1 times
the average covariance.

00:57:01.940 --> 00:57:05.390
When n gets large,
then it turns out

00:57:05.390 --> 00:57:09.110
that the average
variance doesn't matter.

00:57:09.110 --> 00:57:12.080
What is driving the
risk of your portfolio

00:57:12.080 --> 00:57:13.910
has nothing to do
with the variance

00:57:13.910 --> 00:57:15.560
of the individual components.

00:57:15.560 --> 00:57:19.640
What it has to do with is what
the average covariance is.

00:57:19.640 --> 00:57:22.610
That's what's driving the
risk of your portfolio.

00:57:22.610 --> 00:57:24.380
Because you've got a
lot more covariances

00:57:24.380 --> 00:57:26.140
than you do variances.

00:57:26.140 --> 00:57:27.110
OK?

00:57:27.110 --> 00:57:28.760
So this is kind
of a neat insight

00:57:28.760 --> 00:57:31.220
because it says that
it's really important how

00:57:31.220 --> 00:57:33.110
things are related.

00:57:33.110 --> 00:57:35.330
And as those
relationships change,

00:57:35.330 --> 00:57:38.585
the risk of your portfolio
is going to change.

00:57:38.585 --> 00:57:40.460
So getting back to
Lewis's point about what's

00:57:40.460 --> 00:57:42.590
going on in current
markets and what

00:57:42.590 --> 00:57:44.420
caught a lot of
portfolio managers

00:57:44.420 --> 00:57:47.540
by surprise with the
subprime markets,

00:57:47.540 --> 00:57:51.110
if the risk of your portfolio
is approximately given

00:57:51.110 --> 00:57:54.740
by the average covariance
and you've been assuming

00:57:54.740 --> 00:57:58.460
all along that you've got
this big pool of mortgages,

00:57:58.460 --> 00:58:01.730
and the mortgages
are all uncorrelated,

00:58:01.730 --> 00:58:05.600
you've essentially assumed that
you've got virtually no risk.

00:58:05.600 --> 00:58:08.480
Because the average
covariance by assumption

00:58:08.480 --> 00:58:13.180
and by historical
analysis is close to zero.

00:58:13.180 --> 00:58:17.020
But when the real state
market goes down nationally,

00:58:17.020 --> 00:58:20.410
then everybody
starts to default.

00:58:20.410 --> 00:58:24.410
And foreclosures become
very highly correlated.

00:58:24.410 --> 00:58:27.880
And so you can see how
overnight, literally overnight,

00:58:27.880 --> 00:58:29.980
your risks can shoot up.

00:58:29.980 --> 00:58:32.530
And you're not prepared
for that unless you

00:58:32.530 --> 00:58:35.970
know that this is what's
going on in your portfolio.

00:58:35.970 --> 00:58:36.641
Yup?

00:58:36.641 --> 00:58:54.037
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:54.037 --> 00:58:55.120
ANDREW LO: Great question.

00:58:55.120 --> 00:58:58.670
Why should things change
in terms of correlation?

00:58:58.670 --> 00:58:59.740
Well, you know what?

00:58:59.740 --> 00:59:00.940
I'll give you an example.

00:59:00.940 --> 00:59:02.710
I'll give you a
personal example?

00:59:02.710 --> 00:59:05.680
Correlation is a function
of human behavior, right?

00:59:05.680 --> 00:59:09.790
I mean, prices are being
formed by you and I, investors.

00:59:09.790 --> 00:59:13.420
And so correlations simply
means that all of us

00:59:13.420 --> 00:59:16.030
end up doing the same
thing around to same time.

00:59:16.030 --> 00:59:18.270
Right?

00:59:18.270 --> 00:59:21.850
I'm going to be heading to the
airport later on this evening.

00:59:21.850 --> 00:59:24.300
And I don't expect
that there's going

00:59:24.300 --> 00:59:27.300
to be much of a big deal
getting on my flight.

00:59:27.300 --> 00:59:29.970
I'll probably get to the
airport about half an hour,

00:59:29.970 --> 00:59:31.140
45 minutes ahead of time.

00:59:31.140 --> 00:59:32.130
It's just a shuttle.

00:59:32.130 --> 00:59:36.402
So I'm heading to Washington,
so it's not a big deal.

00:59:36.402 --> 00:59:38.360
What's going to happen
in two weeks from today?

00:59:41.320 --> 00:59:42.430
Anything?

00:59:42.430 --> 00:59:45.500
Anything going on two weeks from
today that you can think of?

00:59:45.500 --> 00:59:46.580
Thanksgiving.

00:59:46.580 --> 00:59:50.342
So if I went to the airport
two weeks from today

00:59:50.342 --> 00:59:52.550
and tried to get on that
shuttle half an hour before,

00:59:52.550 --> 00:59:55.460
you think I can
get on the flight?

00:59:55.460 --> 00:59:57.070
Why not?

00:59:57.070 --> 00:59:59.770
Because everybody else
is going to do that.

00:59:59.770 --> 01:00:02.460
Well, why should everything
be correlated on that day?

01:00:02.460 --> 01:00:05.710
Isn't that a Wednesday
like every other Wednesday?

01:00:05.710 --> 01:00:06.740
Well, it's not.

01:00:06.740 --> 01:00:09.400
It's because somehow
we've all decided

01:00:09.400 --> 01:00:11.830
that we're going to take
off at the same time

01:00:11.830 --> 01:00:14.560
on the same day in that year.

01:00:14.560 --> 01:00:15.253
Right?

01:00:15.253 --> 01:00:20.826
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:00:20.826 --> 01:00:23.200
ANDREW LO: Well, first of all,
I don't think Thanksgiving

01:00:23.200 --> 01:00:25.600
is that low a probability.

01:00:25.600 --> 01:00:27.040
OK?

01:00:27.040 --> 01:00:29.950
But to your point, is that
the correlation changing?

01:00:29.950 --> 01:00:31.150
Well, it is.

01:00:31.150 --> 01:00:37.110
Correlation is a statistical
measure of two objects.

01:00:37.110 --> 01:00:40.020
And what we're trying to capture
is when they move up or down

01:00:40.020 --> 01:00:41.160
at the same time.

01:00:41.160 --> 01:00:42.140
Right?

01:00:42.140 --> 01:00:43.890
So what I'm trying to
get at is that there

01:00:43.890 --> 01:00:45.265
are certain periods
of time where

01:00:45.265 --> 01:00:49.750
human behavior, all of a sudden,
becomes very highly correlated.

01:00:49.750 --> 01:00:51.310
And there are many
reasons for that.

01:00:51.310 --> 01:00:53.100
In particular,
Thanksgiving is a reason

01:00:53.100 --> 01:00:56.340
we all decide that Thursday
is this national holiday.

01:00:56.340 --> 01:00:58.615
And therefore, on that
Wednesday, we actually

01:00:58.615 --> 01:01:00.240
have to travel in
order to get to where

01:01:00.240 --> 01:01:02.020
we need to go by Thursday.

01:01:02.020 --> 01:01:02.850
Right?

01:01:02.850 --> 01:01:05.430
But any arbitrary
Wednesday is not

01:01:05.430 --> 01:01:07.380
going to be necessarily
highly correlated.

01:01:07.380 --> 01:01:10.380
So when I go to the airport
on a typical Wednesday,

01:01:10.380 --> 01:01:12.030
I don't expect it to be so bad.

01:01:12.030 --> 01:01:13.710
But on Wednesday
before Thanksgiving,

01:01:13.710 --> 01:01:15.510
it's going to be a madhouse.

01:01:15.510 --> 01:01:16.290
Right?

01:01:16.290 --> 01:01:18.240
That's an example of
a changing correlation

01:01:18.240 --> 01:01:20.730
because of a
particular coordination

01:01:20.730 --> 01:01:22.320
that we've all agreed upon.

01:01:22.320 --> 01:01:24.322
Now that's a relatively
artificial example.

01:01:24.322 --> 01:01:25.530
But I did it to make a point.

01:01:25.530 --> 01:01:26.904
Now let me give
you a real answer

01:01:26.904 --> 01:01:30.250
to your question about why
things may be correlated.

01:01:30.250 --> 01:01:34.390
When we are all scared about
the value of our investments,

01:01:34.390 --> 01:01:37.690
when our fear circuitry
gets triggered,

01:01:37.690 --> 01:01:41.440
what's the natural instinct
for all of us because it's

01:01:41.440 --> 01:01:43.640
hardwired into our brains?

01:01:43.640 --> 01:01:46.060
It's to get to safety.

01:01:46.060 --> 01:01:48.130
It's to get out of
those bad assets

01:01:48.130 --> 01:01:49.630
and get into the good assets.

01:01:49.630 --> 01:01:50.170
Right?

01:01:50.170 --> 01:01:53.710
You saw that three month T-bill
yield at 10 basis points, or 5

01:01:53.710 --> 01:01:54.880
basis points?

01:01:54.880 --> 01:01:57.490
That's a sign that we're
all scared to death

01:01:57.490 --> 01:01:58.960
and we want to get to safety.

01:01:58.960 --> 01:02:00.460
That's an example
of a correlation.

01:02:00.460 --> 01:02:00.960
Why?

01:02:00.960 --> 01:02:04.280
Because everybody is going to
be selling at the same time.

01:02:04.280 --> 01:02:09.140
In a crowded theater, if you
smell smoke and somebody shouts

01:02:09.140 --> 01:02:12.250
fire, what are you going to do?

01:02:12.250 --> 01:02:14.980
It's not rocket
science to predict

01:02:14.980 --> 01:02:17.360
that the four exits
that are out there

01:02:17.360 --> 01:02:20.180
will be a bit
crowded after that.

01:02:20.180 --> 01:02:21.640
Right?

01:02:21.640 --> 01:02:24.590
So correlation is not
a physical quantity.

01:02:24.590 --> 01:02:27.180
That's the problem with
physics and biology.

01:02:27.180 --> 01:02:30.770
Physics has parameters that
don't change over time.

01:02:30.770 --> 01:02:32.720
I wish we could have
that in finance.

01:02:32.720 --> 01:02:33.840
We don't.

01:02:33.840 --> 01:02:35.632
We have parameters that
are not parameters.

01:02:35.632 --> 01:02:36.673
They're random variables.

01:02:36.673 --> 01:02:38.090
They depend on a lot of things.

01:02:38.090 --> 01:02:39.780
Correlation is one of them.

01:02:39.780 --> 01:02:42.410
And until we start recognizing
that correlations are really

01:02:42.410 --> 01:02:44.935
part and partial of
human interactions,

01:02:44.935 --> 01:02:47.060
we're going to continue to
make mistakes like we've

01:02:47.060 --> 01:02:49.270
made over the last 10 years.

01:02:49.270 --> 01:02:52.370
And that's a simple
example of that.

01:02:52.370 --> 01:02:53.122
Other question?

01:02:53.122 --> 01:02:53.622
Yeah.

01:02:53.622 --> 01:02:57.865
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:02:57.865 --> 01:02:58.490
ANDREW LO: Yes.

01:02:58.490 --> 01:03:07.640
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:03:07.640 --> 01:03:09.410
ANDREW LO: Yeah.

01:03:09.410 --> 01:03:10.040
That's true.

01:03:10.040 --> 01:03:11.250
That's possible.

01:03:11.250 --> 01:03:14.720
So you have to decide whether
or not what you're looking at

01:03:14.720 --> 01:03:17.120
is an aberration,
or whether it's

01:03:17.120 --> 01:03:18.590
something that's systematic.

01:03:18.590 --> 01:03:21.440
So for example, if I didn't
know anything about Thanksgiving

01:03:21.440 --> 01:03:24.740
and I happened to travel on
Wednesdays on a regular basis

01:03:24.740 --> 01:03:28.520
to Washington, then
you know, in two weeks,

01:03:28.520 --> 01:03:29.922
I'll get-- it's really crowded.

01:03:29.922 --> 01:03:31.880
And then it won't be
crowded, won't be crowded,

01:03:31.880 --> 01:03:32.930
won't be crowded.

01:03:32.930 --> 01:03:34.970
And pretty soon,
after a while, I'll

01:03:34.970 --> 01:03:37.730
say, well, that was
just a 1% event.

01:03:37.730 --> 01:03:40.040
Of course, next year
it will happen again.

01:03:40.040 --> 01:03:43.470
And then I'll say, gee, you
know, well, that's another 1%,

01:03:43.470 --> 01:03:43.970
kind of.

01:03:43.970 --> 01:03:46.730
But pretty soon I'm going to
realize that, gee, it seems

01:03:46.730 --> 01:03:48.260
like there's a pattern here.

01:03:48.260 --> 01:03:53.620
And that 1%, it's not just
so simple as a 1% error.

01:03:53.620 --> 01:03:57.500
Statistics, remember, is a
mathematical quantification

01:03:57.500 --> 01:03:58.460
of our stupidity.

01:03:58.460 --> 01:03:59.960
Right?

01:03:59.960 --> 01:04:01.150
I mean, what we don't know.

01:04:01.150 --> 01:04:03.650
Well, we don't know why things
happen the way they happen,

01:04:03.650 --> 01:04:05.300
so we put a distribution on it.

01:04:05.300 --> 01:04:06.650
We say that it's normal.

01:04:06.650 --> 01:04:09.650
And we say that there's
5% this way, 5% that way.

01:04:09.650 --> 01:04:11.150
But that just is
a representation

01:04:11.150 --> 01:04:12.170
of our ignorance.

01:04:12.170 --> 01:04:15.699
The more we know, the less we
have to rely on statistics.

01:04:15.699 --> 01:04:17.240
So I don't need
statistics to tell me

01:04:17.240 --> 01:04:18.698
that two weeks from
now, it's going

01:04:18.698 --> 01:04:19.970
to be really crowded at Logan.

01:04:19.970 --> 01:04:22.070
But if I didn't know
about Thanksgiving,

01:04:22.070 --> 01:04:25.460
if I came from Mars and I
was doing a study of airport

01:04:25.460 --> 01:04:27.590
congestion, it would
take me a while

01:04:27.590 --> 01:04:29.480
to get enough data
to figure out that

01:04:29.480 --> 01:04:32.220
once a year on the Wednesday
before the Thursday

01:04:32.220 --> 01:04:35.240
in, you know, November,
it gets crowded.

01:04:35.240 --> 01:04:39.710
So the challenge for all of
you is how much intelligence

01:04:39.710 --> 01:04:41.820
can you bring to the analysis.

01:04:41.820 --> 01:04:44.730
What I'm showing you is
very simple mathematics.

01:04:44.730 --> 01:04:46.820
Mathematics is not enough.

01:04:46.820 --> 01:04:48.620
If you just had the
mathematics, you

01:04:48.620 --> 01:04:50.990
would be losing money,
you know, continuously.

01:04:50.990 --> 01:04:53.990
Because there's just much more
to financial markets than just

01:04:53.990 --> 01:04:54.570
the math.

01:04:54.570 --> 01:04:55.070
OK?

01:04:55.070 --> 01:04:55.903
The math is trivial.

01:04:55.903 --> 01:04:57.660
This is high school algebra.

01:04:57.660 --> 01:04:59.690
But the real key
is to put together

01:04:59.690 --> 01:05:02.120
the framework of economic
and financial analysis

01:05:02.120 --> 01:05:03.830
with the mathematics.

01:05:03.830 --> 01:05:06.500
So let me continue doing that.

01:05:06.500 --> 01:05:11.840
This is another example of
computing the average variance,

01:05:11.840 --> 01:05:13.730
and then looking
at the volatility

01:05:13.730 --> 01:05:17.130
of your particular holdings,
given different correlations.

01:05:17.130 --> 01:05:19.342
So I want you to do
lots of exercises

01:05:19.342 --> 01:05:21.050
where you look at
different correlations.

01:05:21.050 --> 01:05:23.240
I don't ever want you
to take correlation

01:05:23.240 --> 01:05:25.700
as a parameter that
is fixed over time,

01:05:25.700 --> 01:05:26.870
when you apply the stuff.

01:05:26.870 --> 01:05:29.750
When you're doing problem sets
in final exams, that's fine.

01:05:29.750 --> 01:05:31.850
You know, the correlation
is whatever it is.

01:05:31.850 --> 01:05:33.950
But recognize that in
practice, these things

01:05:33.950 --> 01:05:36.200
change a lot over time.

01:05:36.200 --> 01:05:37.820
OK?

01:05:37.820 --> 01:05:41.030
Now the idea behind
correlation is

01:05:41.030 --> 01:05:42.590
that they help
you reduce the ups

01:05:42.590 --> 01:05:45.920
and the downs of the
variance of your portfolio.

01:05:45.920 --> 01:05:49.160
But it turns out that there's
a limit to how much of the risk

01:05:49.160 --> 01:05:50.420
you can reduce.

01:05:50.420 --> 01:05:53.420
And this graph basically
shows that as you

01:05:53.420 --> 01:05:55.370
add more and more securities--

01:05:55.370 --> 01:05:58.190
even though the correlations
are bouncing around--

01:05:58.190 --> 01:06:00.230
as you add more and
more securities,

01:06:00.230 --> 01:06:03.170
there ends up being some
kind of a steady state

01:06:03.170 --> 01:06:07.310
limit to what the variance
of your overall portfolio is.

01:06:07.310 --> 01:06:12.210
After 20, 30, 40,
50, 100 stocks,

01:06:12.210 --> 01:06:14.400
you'll notice that the
variance of your portfolio

01:06:14.400 --> 01:06:17.190
doesn't go down anymore.

01:06:17.190 --> 01:06:21.480
And it turns out that that
limit, whatever that is,

01:06:21.480 --> 01:06:27.120
is what we consider to be
the systematic risk that

01:06:27.120 --> 01:06:29.220
is implicit in the economy.

01:06:29.220 --> 01:06:32.490
In other words, that's the
risk that no matter how well

01:06:32.490 --> 01:06:37.110
diversified you are, you've
got to bear that risk.

01:06:37.110 --> 01:06:38.720
Everybody, all of
us, we have to,

01:06:38.720 --> 01:06:41.690
we can't get any
less risky than that

01:06:41.690 --> 01:06:44.120
unless we start putting
our money in the mattress

01:06:44.120 --> 01:06:45.350
or in T-bills.

01:06:45.350 --> 01:06:46.250
OK?

01:06:46.250 --> 01:06:50.210
That limit is known as the
systematic, or market risk,

01:06:50.210 --> 01:06:51.740
of a portfolio.

01:06:51.740 --> 01:06:55.370
So, see here is the graph
of your portfolio variance

01:06:55.370 --> 01:06:58.010
as you increase more
and more securities.

01:06:58.010 --> 01:07:01.980
But at some point, it
asymptotes to this level,

01:07:01.980 --> 01:07:04.040
which is what I'm going
to be focusing on,

01:07:04.040 --> 01:07:06.440
as undiversifiable risk.

01:07:06.440 --> 01:07:09.110
It's the risk that's
left over after all

01:07:09.110 --> 01:07:11.840
of the various correlations
have done what they

01:07:11.840 --> 01:07:16.040
can to dampen the ups and
the downs of your collection

01:07:16.040 --> 01:07:17.780
of securities.

01:07:17.780 --> 01:07:20.360
And obviously,
there's going to be

01:07:20.360 --> 01:07:22.550
some calculations you'll
need to do to figure out

01:07:22.550 --> 01:07:23.849
what that number is.

01:07:23.849 --> 01:07:25.640
But I want to give you
the intuition first,

01:07:25.640 --> 01:07:27.167
and then we'll do
the calculations.

01:07:27.167 --> 01:07:29.000
And then we're going
to study the properties

01:07:29.000 --> 01:07:30.750
of this hard limit.

01:07:30.750 --> 01:07:32.850
OK?

01:07:32.850 --> 01:07:39.260
Now, I'm about to proceed to
the next stage of our analysis

01:07:39.260 --> 01:07:41.810
where we start
asking the question,

01:07:41.810 --> 01:07:46.431
how do we pick the very
best possible portfolio.

01:07:46.431 --> 01:07:47.930
But before I do, I
want to make sure

01:07:47.930 --> 01:07:49.880
that everybody is comfortable
with the analytics

01:07:49.880 --> 01:07:50.546
we've developed.

01:07:50.546 --> 01:07:53.180
If you have any questions, now
would be a good time to ask.

01:07:53.180 --> 01:07:54.721
Because from this
point on, I'm going

01:07:54.721 --> 01:07:57.980
to assume that you understand
how portfolio theory works,

01:07:57.980 --> 01:08:00.410
the mechanics of
portfolio weights,

01:08:00.410 --> 01:08:03.890
and how to compute means,
variances, covariances,

01:08:03.890 --> 01:08:06.790
and what they imply
for the portfolio.

01:08:06.790 --> 01:08:08.160
Question, yeah?

01:08:08.160 --> 01:08:10.240
AUDIENCE: Earlier,
you said that we

01:08:10.240 --> 01:08:12.860
start from this, ensuring that
the markets are pretty much

01:08:12.860 --> 01:08:13.730
stable.

01:08:13.730 --> 01:08:17.140
But I'm wondering, how
reasonable is that assumption?

01:08:17.140 --> 01:08:23.140
And why would nobody ever pick
