01:08:23.140 --> 01:08:28.170
for example, you know, if there
was a big scandal tomorrow,

01:08:28.170 --> 01:08:31.390
like a corruption, like
I'm thinking about Enron

01:08:31.390 --> 01:08:35.080
or [INAUDIBLE] in Italy.

01:08:35.080 --> 01:08:39.710
Why would I not want to
short sell, you know,

01:08:39.710 --> 01:08:46.466
the higher return stock and
buy the lower return stock,

01:08:46.466 --> 01:08:48.960
and take the lower
part of the curve?

01:08:48.960 --> 01:08:53.160
ANDREW LO: You might, if
there are other elements that

01:08:53.160 --> 01:08:55.410
are in this analysis.

01:08:55.410 --> 01:08:58.020
So as I said, this
analysis assumes

01:08:58.020 --> 01:09:02.319
there are only two dimensions,
mean and standard deviation.

01:09:02.319 --> 01:09:03.359
Right?

01:09:03.359 --> 01:09:05.189
You've now introduced
a third, which

01:09:05.189 --> 01:09:08.850
is corporate responsibility
or corporate governance

01:09:08.850 --> 01:09:10.439
or fraud or something like that.

01:09:10.439 --> 01:09:12.240
Then you would need
three dimensions.

01:09:12.240 --> 01:09:16.680
And there'd be something
sticking outside the screen.

01:09:16.680 --> 01:09:19.470
And then you'd have to choose
among the three possibilities.

01:09:19.470 --> 01:09:21.420
So it's possible
that you want to be

01:09:21.420 --> 01:09:25.890
down here because this company
has a better reputation

01:09:25.890 --> 01:09:28.470
than this one up here.

01:09:28.470 --> 01:09:30.210
But then what
you're telling me is

01:09:30.210 --> 01:09:34.439
that reputation matters to
you beyond standard deviation

01:09:34.439 --> 01:09:37.600
and expected return.

01:09:37.600 --> 01:09:38.715
What's that?

01:09:38.715 --> 01:09:40.456
AUDIENCE: Market conditions.

01:09:40.456 --> 01:09:42.330
ANDREW LO: Stable means
that these parameters

01:09:42.330 --> 01:09:45.857
are likely to stay
the same over time.

01:09:45.857 --> 01:09:47.732
AUDIENCE: There's a
