01:13:17.690 --> 01:13:18.190
Right?

01:13:18.190 --> 01:13:20.000
That's what hedge
funds try to do.

01:13:20.000 --> 01:13:22.730
They try to figure out
how all of these relations

01:13:22.730 --> 01:13:25.550
impact on how to construct
a good portfolio.

01:13:25.550 --> 01:13:26.348
All right?

01:13:26.348 --> 01:13:28.360
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:13:28.360 --> 01:13:29.360
ANDREW LO: That's right.

01:13:29.360 --> 01:13:30.170
For example.

01:13:30.170 --> 01:13:31.929
That would be one
way of looking at it.

01:13:31.929 --> 01:13:32.970
But there are other ways.

01:13:32.970 --> 01:13:34.550
It doesn't have to
be quantitative.

01:13:34.550 --> 01:13:36.110
There are a lot of talented
hedge fund managers

01:13:36.110 --> 01:13:37.670
that don't know how
to use a calculator,

01:13:37.670 --> 01:13:38.503
make a lot of money.

01:13:38.503 --> 01:13:40.100
OK?

01:13:40.100 --> 01:13:42.795
So don't think that it's all
about quantitative analysis.

01:13:42.795 --> 01:13:43.670
That's what we think.

01:13:43.670 --> 01:13:45.140
That's how I think.

01:13:45.140 --> 01:13:46.994
That's how MIT may think.

01:13:46.994 --> 01:13:49.160
But that's not the only way
to make money out there.

01:13:49.160 --> 01:13:50.870
You know, Warren
Buffett, I don't think

01:13:50.870 --> 01:13:53.210
knows how to calculate
