01:13:53.210 --> 01:13:56.250
But he's done OK.

01:13:56.250 --> 01:13:59.270
So but I think what we can
do with this framework is

01:13:59.270 --> 01:14:02.570
to analyze how he
does what he does,

01:14:02.570 --> 01:14:06.130
and understand it in the context
of this kind of a framework.

01:14:06.130 --> 01:14:06.860
All right.

01:14:06.860 --> 01:14:12.470
So let's now go to the next
topic, which is, all right,

01:14:12.470 --> 01:14:15.710
how do we choose
a good portfolio,

01:14:15.710 --> 01:14:18.410
given what we now know
about this framework?

01:14:18.410 --> 01:14:19.989
Well, we said before--

01:14:19.989 --> 01:14:21.530
Ryan pointed out--
that we never want

01:14:21.530 --> 01:14:24.410
to be on the lower
part of that frontier.

01:14:24.410 --> 01:14:25.830
So that's one thing we know.

01:14:25.830 --> 01:14:26.330
Right?

01:14:26.330 --> 01:14:28.810
We don't want to be
on the bottom part.

01:14:28.810 --> 01:14:31.190
So we want to be on
the efficient frontier.

01:14:31.190 --> 01:14:34.310
Now this entire
bullet can be viewed

01:14:34.310 --> 01:14:37.550
as what's called the
minimum variance boundary.

01:14:37.550 --> 01:14:40.940
Meaning, for any given
investment over here,

01:14:40.940 --> 01:14:44.390
we have the absolute
minimum variance

01:14:44.390 --> 01:14:46.850
that has the same level
of expected return.

01:14:46.850 --> 01:14:49.490
So when I go, when
I go horizontally,

01:14:49.490 --> 01:14:52.040
I'm looking at the
smallest amount

01:14:52.040 --> 01:14:56.260
of risk I can take for
that same level of expected

01:14:56.260 --> 01:14:57.060
rate of return.

01:14:57.060 --> 01:15:00.680
That's what this bullet can
be viewed as giving you.

01:15:00.680 --> 01:15:05.610
And it turns out that because
we like expected return,

01:15:05.610 --> 01:15:07.790
and we don't like
risk, we want to be

01:15:07.790 --> 01:15:09.680
on the upper part
of that bullet.

01:15:09.680 --> 01:15:13.500
So this upper part is known
as the efficient frontier.

01:15:13.500 --> 01:15:16.680
So that's the one thing we can
tell about portfolio theory.

01:15:16.680 --> 01:15:20.060
It's that we want to
be on the upper branch.

01:15:20.060 --> 01:15:21.920
But where on the
upper branch depends

01:15:21.920 --> 01:15:23.830
upon our risk preferences.

01:15:23.830 --> 01:15:25.370
OK?

01:15:25.370 --> 01:15:27.650
So here's a concrete example.

01:15:27.650 --> 01:15:30.500
Suppose you can invest in
any combination of General

01:15:30.500 --> 01:15:32.540
Motors, IBM, and Motorola.

01:15:32.540 --> 01:15:35.010
What portfolio would you choose?

01:15:35.010 --> 01:15:37.260
So these are the data
that you would start with.

01:15:37.260 --> 01:15:37.760
OK?

01:15:37.760 --> 01:15:41.030
The means and the standard
deviations, and then of course,

01:15:41.030 --> 01:15:42.050
the covariances.

01:15:42.050 --> 01:15:43.820
You've got to have
the covariances to be

01:15:43.820 --> 01:15:46.250
able to calculate that bullet.

01:15:46.250 --> 01:15:50.154
So you can invest
in any combination.

01:15:50.154 --> 01:15:51.070
What would you choose?

01:15:51.070 --> 01:15:53.890
Let's calculate the
expected rate of return

01:15:53.890 --> 01:15:57.730
and the variance
of that portfolio.

01:15:57.730 --> 01:16:00.550
And you want to ask
the question, what

01:16:00.550 --> 01:16:02.430
looks good to you?

01:16:02.430 --> 01:16:04.200
OK?

01:16:04.200 --> 01:16:06.480
Well, it turns out
that when you calculate

01:16:06.480 --> 01:16:09.570
this kind of a bullet,
you find out something

01:16:09.570 --> 01:16:13.810
that's, yet again, amazing.

01:16:13.810 --> 01:16:17.560
What you find is that
the bullet actually

01:16:17.560 --> 01:16:22.820
is better than any of the three
stocks that you started with.

01:16:22.820 --> 01:16:24.640
So look at where the
three stocks are--

01:16:24.640 --> 01:16:27.517
General Motors,
IBM, and Motorola--

01:16:27.517 --> 01:16:29.350
and the bullet, look
at where the bullet is.

01:16:29.350 --> 01:16:35.160
The bullet is strictly to the
northwest of these stocks.

01:16:35.160 --> 01:16:35.730
Right?

01:16:35.730 --> 01:16:38.850
In other words, you can do
better than any one of these,

01:16:38.850 --> 01:16:41.370
either by going here
or by going here.

01:16:41.370 --> 01:16:43.830
For the same level of risk,
you can get a higher return.

01:16:43.830 --> 01:16:47.980
For the same level of expected
return, you can get lower risk.

01:16:47.980 --> 01:16:49.450
OK?

01:16:49.450 --> 01:16:52.450
So the first point is
that portfolio theory,

01:16:52.450 --> 01:16:55.600
for multiple stocks, is
even more compelling.

01:16:55.600 --> 01:16:57.530
Because now, with
those two stocks,

01:16:57.530 --> 01:17:02.290
at least the two stocks were on
that minimum variance boundary.

01:17:02.290 --> 01:17:05.050
Now, with three
stocks and more, it's

01:17:05.050 --> 01:17:07.360
possible that none
of the stocks are

01:17:07.360 --> 01:17:10.080
going to be on the
minimum variance boundary.

01:17:10.080 --> 01:17:10.898
Yeah?

